==English==
===Etymology===
From [[Αncient Greek]] [[Ωκεανός]] (''okeanos'') "[[ocean]]", from [[ωκύς]] (''okys'') "fast, quick, swift" + [[νάω]] (''nao'') " to flow, to flux".

===Proper noun===
'''Oceanus'''
{{wikipedia}}
#{{greekmyth}}: Personification of vast waters or the world ocean. He was the first-born of the  Titans, son of [[Uranus]] and [[Gaia]], the god [[Ωκεανός]] [[Ποταμός]] (River Ocean) that encircled the earth. With his sister [[Tethys]] fathered all rivers and the [[Oceanids]].

